00:09:00.560 --> 00:09:04.600
Random fact: machine-spun
cotton candy was invented in 1897

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:07.979
by the dentist William Morrison
and confectioner John C. Wharton,

00:09:07.980 --> 00:09:12.980
and first introduced to a wide audience
at the 1904 World's Fair as "Fairy Floss."

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:18.220
Our vitamin B2 glowing cotton candy.

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:20.340
This is glowing under a black
light because the riboflavin

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:23.720
was in such a fine powder
that it was actually able to be carried

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:26.850
and mixed in evenly
with all of the spun sugar.

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:28.040
It's a pretty cool effect.

00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:30.040
I do have to say,
if you're trying this,

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:31.820
you want to be really
careful about your balance

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:34.120
between the sugar
and the riboflavin,

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:35.900
because it does have
kind of a bitter taste.

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:37.260
So, if you have too much of it,

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:39.120
your cotton candy
will end up tasting bitter.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:41.460
So, you want to just barely have enough

00:09:41.460 --> 00:09:43.200
that it starts showing up
under the black light.

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.040
Otherwise, it's not
going to taste great.

00:09:46.220 --> 00:09:48.560
Lots of types of hard candy
work in this machine,

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:50.420
including making our own hard candy.

00:09:50.420 --> 00:09:53.720
Adding a little bit of vitamin B2
can actually make the cotton candy

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:55.880
